00:00:13.580 --> 00:00:19.696
RAMONA ROMERO: Good afternoon, Welcome.

00:00:19.696 --> 00:00:23.260
You're a really scary group of people.

00:00:23.260 --> 00:00:28.320
Thank you so much

00:00:28.320 --> 00:00:32.220
for being here.
It is great that you came back to the

00:00:32.220 --> 00:00:35.220
University to celebrate the
contributions that women have made to

00:00:35.220 --> 00:00:42.150
Princeton and to society. My name is
Ramona Romero and you can take as many

00:00:42.150 --> 00:00:51.600
pictures with me as you want okay? Just
no pictures of the justices after a

00:00:51.600 --> 00:00:56.640
couple of minutes. My name is Ramona
Romero and for almost four years I have

00:00:56.640 --> 00:01:06.690
been the general counsel of the
University. As a lawyer, as a lawyer it is

00:01:06.690 --> 00:01:13.080
a true true honor for me to introduce
three legal superstars, Supreme Court

00:01:13.080 --> 00:01:22.770
Justice Sonia Sotomayor, Class of 19--

00:01:22.770 --> 00:01:33.930
Class of 1976, Justice Elena Kagan Class

00:01:33.930 --> 00:01:37.850
Class of 1981,

00:01:38.659 --> 00:01:49.950
and Heather Gerken, Class of 1991, the
recently appointed dean of the Yale Law

00:01:49.950 --> 00:01:57.420
School. As the lawyers in the audience
know, the Supreme Court begins its term

00:01:57.420 --> 00:02:02.820
on the first Monday in October, so we are
particularly grateful to the justices

00:02:02.820 --> 00:02:11.479
for having come today during this very,
very busy week. We're also very grateful --

00:02:12.019 --> 00:02:20.010
that was unintentional -- we're also
grateful to Dean Gerken, who has also had

00:02:20.010 --> 00:02:27.330
an unusually demanding beginning of the
term. This could take a long time guys. So

00:02:27.330 --> 00:02:34.050
you know, I first met Dean Gerken a few
years ago when I was new to Princeton

00:02:34.050 --> 00:02:40.050
and she was a University trustee. Based
on our interactions, her unassuming

00:02:40.050 --> 00:02:44.940
manner would give you no clue of her
many accomplishments. After graduating

00:02:44.940 --> 00:02:49.170
from Princeton summa cum laude, she
earned her degree from the University of

00:02:49.170 --> 00:02:55.019
Michigan Law School again with the
highest honors. Following her clerkship

00:02:55.019 --> 00:02:59.299
on the 9th circuit and for Justice
David Souter on the U.S. Supreme Court,

00:02:59.299 --> 00:03:05.220
she worked at a law firm for a few years.
A mutual friend who was a colleague of

00:03:05.220 --> 00:03:11.579
hers at the law firm describes her as
phenomenally talented and too good for

00:03:11.579 --> 00:03:20.910
the law firm world. Dean Gerken entered
academia in the year 2000, earning tenure

00:03:20.910 --> 00:03:28.980
at Harvard and then at Yale. When she was
appointed dean last year, the first woman

00:03:28.980 --> 00:03:36.389
to hold that position,

00:03:37.209 --> 00:03:43.760
Dean Gerken's predecessor said that
Yale Law School is very lucky to be able

00:03:43.760 --> 00:03:49.430
to draw on the energy, brilliance and
leadership of Heather Gerken. This is a

00:03:49.430 --> 00:03:54.920
time of change in our country and in
legal education, and Heather is perfectly

00:03:54.920 --> 00:04:00.050
suited to take the helm of this
extraordinary place. And I think we've

00:04:00.050 --> 00:04:05.810
seen evidence of that already, but lest
you think that Dean Gerken is all

00:04:05.810 --> 00:04:10.819
about legal scholarship, I encourage you
to Google her name after the program's

00:04:10.819 --> 00:04:18.889
over, to Google her name and the words
vampire novel. Now on to the toughest

00:04:18.889 --> 00:04:24.290
part of my assignment, introducing two
women who really need no introduction,

00:04:24.290 --> 00:04:31.280
Justices Sonia Maria Sotomayor and
Elena Kagan. Justice Kagan and Sotomayor

00:04:31.280 --> 00:04:43.610
have much in common. Both are from New
York and both -- clock is ticking -- but

00:04:43.610 --> 00:04:48.500
are from New York and both are serious
baseball fans, although they had although

00:04:48.500 --> 00:04:53.000
they do favor different teams and only
one of those teams is doing well.

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:59.360
At Princeton both majored in history, excelled
academically, and graduated with the

00:04:59.360 --> 00:05:04.789
highest honors. Since they left our
campus, both have blazed many trails. For

00:05:04.789 --> 00:05:09.680
example, Justice Kagan was the first
female dean of the Harvard Law School

00:05:09.680 --> 00:05:14.930
and she was also the first woman and so
far the only woman to serve as Solicitor

00:05:14.930 --> 00:05:18.160
General of the United States.

00:05:21.360 --> 00:05:26.800
Justice Sotomayor is the first and only
Hispanic American ever appointed to the

00:05:26.800 --> 00:05:32.260
U.S. Supreme Court

00:05:32.260 --> 00:05:37.060
and the first and only woman of color to
ever serve on that court. Clock is

00:05:42.230 --> 00:05:47.960
ticking guys. After graduating from
Princeton, Justices Kagan and Sotomayor

00:05:47.960 --> 00:05:51.800
traveled different paths to their
appointments as the third and fourth

00:05:51.800 --> 00:05:57.350
female justices in our nation's history.
Justice Sotomayor, who

00:05:57.350 --> 00:06:02.330
attended Yale Law School, honed her
courtroom skill as a prosecutor in New

00:06:02.330 --> 00:06:08.060
York, worked at a law firm, and spent 17
years as a federal trial and appellate

00:06:08.060 --> 00:06:13.460
judge before her elevation to the
Supreme Court in 2009. She issued

00:06:13.460 --> 00:06:19.630
hundreds of decisions. However none is
better known than a decision she issued

00:06:19.630 --> 00:06:23.780
enjoining
that an injunction she issued that

00:06:23.780 --> 00:06:29.870
effectively ended a baseball strike that
had forced the cancellation of the 1994

00:06:29.870 --> 00:06:35.930
World Series. As a former baseball Major
League Baseball player testified during

00:06:35.930 --> 00:06:39.169
her confirmation hearing, with one
decision

00:06:39.169 --> 00:06:44.990
she brought players and owners back to
the table and rescued the 1995 baseball

00:06:44.990 --> 00:06:54.320
season. So you see, putting aside Justice
Oliver Wendell Holmes, who authored a

00:06:54.320 --> 00:07:00.200
mystifying to lawyers Supreme Court
opinion in 1922 that exempted baseball

00:07:00.200 --> 00:07:05.150
from the antitrust laws, I think it is
safe to say the Sonia Sotomayor is the

00:07:05.150 --> 00:07:10.250
only justice in our nation's history who
can take credit for saving the national

00:07:10.250 --> 00:07:12.790
pastime.

00:07:17.810 --> 00:07:23.880
When Justice Sotomayor was nominated to
the Supreme Court New York, district

00:07:23.880 --> 00:07:28.860
attorney Robert Morgenthau 
noted that throughout her career she had

00:07:28.860 --> 00:07:36.120
exhibited wisdom, intelligence,
collegiality, and good character. New York

00:07:36.120 --> 00:07:41.880
City Mayor Michael Bloomberg praised her
sharp and agile mind, her wealth of

00:07:41.880 --> 00:07:46.740
unique experience, and fact that she
is an independent jurist

00:07:46.740 --> 00:07:51.660
who does not fit squarely into an
ideological box. Her appointment was a

00:07:51.660 --> 00:07:57.060
particularly joyful and proud moment for
the Hispanic legal community.

00:07:57.060 --> 00:08:02.130
She was active within our communities
throughout her 17 years on the bench and

00:08:02.130 --> 00:08:10.040
was and remains deeply respected and
beloved not only for her accomplishments

00:08:10.040 --> 00:08:15.870
but also for her extraordinary
commitment to giving back. As someone

00:08:15.870 --> 00:08:21.630
who knows her well said to me recently,
her commitment is authentic. She has

00:08:21.630 --> 00:08:26.400
never forgotten her roots in the South
Bronx, prefers Puerto Rican food above

00:08:26.400 --> 00:08:30.210
all others, and means everything she says
and does.

00:08:30.210 --> 00:08:36.710
She's also, based on my own observations
over the years, one of the most genuine,

00:08:36.710 --> 00:08:43.130
gracious, humble, and decent 
people on the planet.

00:08:49.270 --> 00:08:56.320
Now Justice Kagan, her post-Princeton path to the Supreme Court

00:08:56.320 --> 00:09:00.670
was equally impressive. After she earned
her law degree from Harvard Law School,

00:09:00.670 --> 00:09:06.070
she clerk on the Court of Appeals in D.C.
and for Justice Marshall on the U.S.

00:09:06.070 --> 00:09:11.860
Supreme Court. Following her clerkship,
she ventured ever so briefly into

00:09:11.860 --> 00:09:17.260
private practice. Subsequently she taught
at the University of Chicago and at

00:09:17.260 --> 00:09:22.570
Harvard, where she later became dean and
served in both the Clinton and Obama

00:09:22.570 --> 00:09:28.209
administrations. A mutual friend who
worked with Justice Kagan when she was a

00:09:28.209 --> 00:09:32.950
counselor to President Clinton told me
that she is known as a brilliant jurist

00:09:32.950 --> 00:09:37.990
for her talents range far beyond
that. As dean of the Harvard Law School

00:09:37.990 --> 00:09:43.240
she was beloved because  she was
approachable and responsive to students

00:09:43.240 --> 00:09:50.230
and faculty, and I'm happy to add alumni
to that list. A few years after

00:09:50.230 --> 00:09:55.779
she became dean, Justice Kagan
hosted the law school's first-ever reunion

00:09:55.779 --> 00:10:01.779
of Hispanic alumni. A large group of us
met with her. We were determined and I

00:10:01.779 --> 00:10:06.730
mean determined to find out what she
intended to do to correct the law school's

00:10:06.730 --> 00:10:13.149
failure to hire Hispanic faculty. Over a
decade later, I still remember how

00:10:13.149 --> 00:10:18.339
impressed I was by the directness and by
the grace and humor with which she

00:10:18.339 --> 00:10:24.130
handled our spirited questioning. Those
qualities including her sense of humor

00:10:24.130 --> 00:10:30.040
were apparent in her confirmation
hearing in 2010. There, to quote President

00:10:30.040 --> 00:10:35.529
Obama, the members of the Senate
Judiciary Committee got a good sense of

00:10:35.529 --> 00:10:39.700
her judicial philosophy, her commitment
to the rule of law,

00:10:39.700 --> 00:10:45.430
her rich understanding of our
Constitution, and of course where she can

00:10:45.430 --> 00:10:48.750
be found on Christmas Day.

00:10:48.959 --> 00:10:55.300
Let me conclude by acknowledging
 how fortunate we are that

00:10:55.300 --> 00:11:01.420
these three women have chosen lives of
service and are now in positions, in

00:11:01.420 --> 00:11:07.630
positions to influence the evolution of
American law. As Justice Kagan -- As Justice

00:11:07.630 --> 00:11:11.769
[inaudible] of the Massachusetts
Supreme Court said during Justice

00:11:11.769 --> 00:11:16.360
Kagan's confirmation hearing, the
presence of women and minorities on a

00:11:16.360 --> 00:11:21.550
court has an impact on the overall
decision-making that goes beyond the

00:11:21.550 --> 00:11:27.519
opinions of the female or
minority judges themselves. They

00:11:27.519 --> 00:11:33.850
influence how the other judges think
and how they analyze the law. Justice

00:11:33.850 --> 00:11:40.630
Sotomayor, Justice Kagan thank you for
your service to the American people and

00:11:40.630 --> 00:11:46.029
for being here today to share your
unique experiences and thank you Dean

00:11:46.029 --> 00:11:51.010
Gerken for moderating today's
conversation and for your contributions

00:11:51.010 --> 00:11:56.170
to legal scholarship and for your
courage and leadership at this time in

00:11:56.170 --> 00:11:59.310
our nation's history.

