to the chase as I know you do not want
to hear from me. And we have a series of

00:13:13.950 --> 00:13:17.640
questions that you have all helped
shape with your own contributions that

00:13:17.640 --> 00:13:21.060
I'm going to ask the justices over the
course of the evening - about their life

00:13:21.060 --> 00:13:25.410
here at Princeton, their careers, advice
they'd have for all the young women in

00:13:25.410 --> 00:13:30.779
the room. So I'll just get started and
just start with something very short. So

00:13:30.779 --> 00:13:35.130
one of you came from Manhattan and
another came from the Bronx. Why did you

00:13:35.130 --> 00:13:39.000
come to Princeton University? And, Chris,
yes, I am setting this up for you so that

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:43.940
you can put it on the website.
[LAUGHTER]

00:13:43.940 --> 00:13:53.160
SONIA SOTOMAYOR: Well for me it was my high school 
coach in debate club, and he guided, got guided

00:13:53.160 --> 00:13:58.080
to Princeton by one of the teachers at
our high school. We were not a feeder

00:13:58.080 --> 00:14:06.959
school and Kenny was the first of our
high school graduates to attend an Ivy

00:14:06.959 --> 00:14:12.720
League school and he came to Princeton
and obviously he didn't flunk out and they took

00:14:12.720 --> 00:14:19.440
a chance on me. It is a long story for
those who - I've said it at the first She

00:14:19.440 --> 00:14:26.190
Roars, so you may have to listen to that
tape. But suffice it to say, I went to

00:14:26.190 --> 00:14:34.560
Harvard and I met an interviewer who was
dressed in a black dress, beautifully

00:14:34.560 --> 00:14:41.649
white coffered hair, pearled earrings, a
black and white poodle next to her,

00:14:41.649 --> 00:14:51.129
a red rug oriental rug in a white couch.
Now in my house, all couches had plastic

00:14:51.129 --> 00:15:00.369
on them and you never bought a white
couch because the kids would mess it up.

00:15:00.369 --> 00:15:06.910
I literally ran out of that room. It's
the only time I've run away from

00:15:06.910 --> 00:15:14.800
something and left and told the assistant -
ELENA KAGAN: Wait, so you went to Princeton instead?

00:15:14.800 --> 00:15:20.139
SOTOMAYOR: I did. I went - [LAUGHTER] 
And I'm going to tell the story of why. I went,

00:15:20.139 --> 00:15:25.480
I tried out Harvard. They were too
radical for me. This is an amazing story.

00:15:25.480 --> 00:15:31.300
But I came to Princeton and my friend,
who was my friend, and he had a bunch of

00:15:31.300 --> 00:15:37.449
other friends that were like him and not
like most Princetonians

00:15:37.449 --> 00:15:48.370
and I got fooled. [LAUGHTER] And that's how I 
ended up here. There is a reason to have posses

00:15:48.370 --> 00:15:53.110
around you. For those of you in education,
you know that there are many colleges

00:15:53.110 --> 00:15:58.540
who bring kids from similar
neighborhoods if they want to integrate

00:15:58.540 --> 00:16:04.720
their schools better because there is a
comfort in meeting people who are more

00:16:04.720 --> 00:16:12.759
like you at least at first. I obviously
got used to Princeton but it does take a

00:16:12.759 --> 00:16:16.980
while if you're from a different environment.
GERKEN: Justice Kagan?

00:16:17.529 --> 00:16:22.839
KAGAN: Well I'm not quite sure why I came to
Princeton. Actually first off I want to

00:16:22.839 --> 00:16:26.009
say it's great to be here.
[APPLAUSE, CHEERS]

