and it's absolutely wonderful to be here

00:16:45.340 --> 00:16:50.650
and to be here especially at an event
like this. Give yourselves some applause.

00:16:50.650 --> 00:16:58.760
What? [APPLAUSE] Wow. Wow. What a crowd. 
SOTOMAYOR: I would have never

00:16:58.760 --> 00:17:01.300
imagined a crowd like this when I came here. No,

00:17:01.300 --> 00:17:07.000
I mean, we were, that I was in the third
year of women, you were in the fifth.

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:12.370
I had many classes where I was the only
woman in the room. To see a gymnasium

00:17:12.370 --> 00:17:18.390
filled of alumni and to see all the
women students up there? [APPLAUSE]

00:17:26.120 --> 00:17:34.640
KAGAN: So I went to a great public school  in New York, Hunter College High

00:17:34.640 --> 00:17:42.740
School. Yeah. Very few people 
went to Princeton from

00:17:42.740 --> 00:17:46.910
my high school. [inaudible] It sent a lot of 
people to a lot of Ivy League schools, but but

00:17:46.910 --> 00:17:52.970
Princeton was not on the list.
And, but I came down here and I just fell

00:17:52.970 --> 00:17:56.240
in love with the place. It was one of
those glorious spring days and the

00:17:56.240 --> 00:18:02.300
campus was looking incredibly beautiful.
And you know what basically I kind of

00:18:02.300 --> 00:18:06.440
think that people do not know what
they're doing when they're 17 and

00:18:06.440 --> 00:18:09.811
they're picking colleges. 
GERKEN: I'm looking at my daughter who's 16.

00:18:09.811 --> 00:18:10.760
KAGAN: Yeah I would love to

00:18:10.760 --> 00:18:14.480
be able to say I had a great reason for
coming to Princeton, but mostly it was I

00:18:14.480 --> 00:18:18.456
caught it on a really sunny beautiful day.
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:18.456 --> 00:18:21.770
GERKEN: Justice Sotomayor, 
you were just talking a little bit

00:18:21.770 --> 00:18:26.120
about the few years after women were
admitted here. You've described

00:18:26.120 --> 00:18:29.600
yourself publicly as a fish out of water
at Princeton. I wonder if you might say a

00:18:29.600 --> 00:18:32.800
little bit more about what that was like.

00:18:32.810 --> 00:18:38.150
SOTOMAYOR: It's hard to describe to people. 
I might I think my favorite story is a couple of

00:18:38.150 --> 00:18:44.870
days into being here. I'm sitting outside
of Dillon Gym and there is a classmate

00:18:44.870 --> 00:18:52.250
there who's from Alabama. Yep
and she starts talking to me about how

00:18:52.250 --> 00:18:57.820
her great-grandfather had been in
Princeton, her grandfather, her father, and

00:18:57.820 --> 00:19:05.390
two of her brothers, and how amazing it
was for her now to join their ranks. And

00:19:05.390 --> 00:19:11.150
I am sort of looking at this, and I'm the
first generation going to college in my

00:19:11.150 --> 00:19:17.840
family, and I'm thinking how many
generations is that. But coming up to me

00:19:17.840 --> 00:19:20.990
were my roommate, who was a
Mexican-American,

00:19:20.990 --> 00:19:25.670
and a Puerto Rican friend, and they were
talking Spanish. And the young woman

00:19:25.670 --> 00:19:31.160
standing, next sitting next to me says,
That's why I love this place. It has so

00:19:31.160 --> 00:19:37.100
many different people. And I'm looking at
her with her Southern drawl and

00:19:37.100 --> 00:19:43.700
thinking, And I thought you were the
different one. But the longer I stayed at

00:19:43.700 --> 00:19:48.620
Princeton, the more different I felt
than most of my classmates. Remember I

00:19:48.620 --> 00:19:53.900
don't think it's as true today. This
was this this was the most non-northern

00:19:53.900 --> 00:20:00.350
school of the South. That's what it was
most famous for and that environment had

00:20:00.350 --> 00:20:07.280
eating clubs and not all the Ivies did
at the time. And it was just opening its

00:20:07.280 --> 00:20:11.600
doors to women, and there were still a
lot of alumni who were not happy with

00:20:11.600 --> 00:20:18.160
that state of affairs. And I think most
of the men on campus liked it a lot, but

00:20:18.160 --> 00:20:24.140
there were still some who really would
have preferred an all-male college or

00:20:24.140 --> 00:20:32.110
university. And so when you feel like a
fish out of water, I don't think you ever

00:20:32.110 --> 00:20:39.430
completely get past it. If you want to
know when I finally figured out I belong,

00:20:39.430 --> 00:20:43.510
when they made me a trustee.

00:20:47.830 --> 00:20:55.299
That's not to say that I didn't identify
as a Princetonian, because I did, and it

00:20:55.299 --> 00:21:02.950
likely was the most influential
experience of my life in terms of

00:21:02.950 --> 00:21:10.309
transforming me from the world I came
from into the world I was entering. But

00:21:10.309 --> 00:21:18.830
it I think I said it best when I
accepted a prize at the end of my four

00:21:18.830 --> 00:21:26.330
years, which is, We all march to different
drummers and the beauty of a place like

00:21:26.330 --> 00:21:32.149
Princeton is to let all of us march to
our own drummers while still being on

00:21:32.149 --> 00:21:39.350
the same parade ground. And so that was
important to me.

00:21:39.350 --> 00:21:42.950
