And you know some well I did my junior
paper with him, my junior paper

00:22:45.120 --> 00:22:48.600
in the spring, and then my senior thesis.
And Sean Wilentz taught me how to write,

00:22:48.600 --> 00:22:56.220
which is a useful thing to know. And and
and so I'm I'm forever grateful to him

00:22:56.220 --> 00:23:00.809
for that and for all the advice he gave
me along the way and for convincing me

00:23:00.809 --> 00:23:05.670
that I really didn't want to be a
historian after all.

00:23:05.670 --> 00:23:07.200
GERKEN: You wrote him 153 pages.

00:23:07.200 --> 00:23:13.710
KAGAN: I did yeah. 150 pages on a subject
that was sort of the bane of my

00:23:13.710 --> 00:23:19.049
existence as I was going through my
confirmation proceedings, because I wrote

00:23:19.049 --> 00:23:27.360
on the history of the Socialist Party
in New York City, in the early

00:23:27.360 --> 00:23:34.049
20th century, and from this everybody
assumed that I must be a socialist.

00:23:34.049 --> 00:23:38.200
And so, and you know -
SOTOMAYOR: She's not?

00:23:38.200 --> 00:23:40.020
KAGAN: This year that's a popular.
This year

00:23:40.020 --> 00:23:43.799
This year that's popular. It was not so
popular among many members of the

00:23:43.799 --> 00:23:50.280
Judiciary Committee when I was trying to
get through the process. But you know the

00:23:50.280 --> 00:23:54.630
judges I clerked for were 
unbelievable in different ways.

00:23:54.630 --> 00:24:00.690
Judge Mikva was somebody who had
served in all different parts of

00:24:00.690 --> 00:24:04.410
government and then he ended up being
really important to my career, not only

00:24:04.410 --> 00:24:08.549
because what he taught me when I was a
clerk for him, but because he ended up at

00:24:08.549 --> 00:24:12.059
the White House. And one day I picked up
the phone, I was teaching at the

00:24:12.059 --> 00:24:17.070
University of Chicago at the time, and
and Judge Mikva said come back and work

00:24:17.070 --> 00:24:22.110
for me at the White House. So it was my
entry into a place that, you know, I never

00:24:22.110 --> 00:24:27.000
expected to be. And I spent four years
there, and it was, it was, it was very

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:33.480
important for just really all the rest
of my of my career. And Justice Marshall,

00:24:33.480 --> 00:24:38.190
it was just an amazing experience
clerking for Justice Marshall, clerking

00:24:38.190 --> 00:24:46.380
for one of the icons of American law and
American history. And you know, he -

00:24:46.380 --> 00:24:51.650
I guess it was the year that I
spent with him

00:24:51.650 --> 00:25:01.730
that just put into my head, You have to
use what you've been given to - what he

00:25:01.730 --> 00:25:06.530
did of course was to promote justice for
more people in more ways than pretty

00:25:06.530 --> 00:25:13.210
much anybody else in the legal
profession in his time. And one can

00:25:13.480 --> 00:25:20.330
one can never think that one is going to
do that, but but but that's a really

00:25:20.330 --> 00:25:22.920
important thing to have in your head as
a goal.

00:25:22.920 --> 00:25:24.380
GERKEN: So Justice Sotomayor, may I ask

00:25:24.380 --> 00:25:27.800
the same question of you, because you may not
know you have this in common, but both of

00:25:27.800 --> 00:25:31.910
you apparently have written
extraordinarily long theses. Seniors out

00:25:31.910 --> 00:25:37.310
there get time to get snapping. So Peter
Wynn was your adviser, and he called your

00:25:37.310 --> 00:25:43.670
thesis, and I quote, "extremely ambitious
and one of the longest I have ever supervised" but I

00:25:43.670 --> 00:25:47.800
wonder if you also might say a few words
about mentors along the way.

00:25:47.800 --> 00:25:52.910
SOTOMAYOR: I'll approach the question a little
differently, which is how do you pick a

00:25:52.910 --> 00:25:59.740
mentor? Well first of all I'm not sure
you pick them. They mostly pick you. And

00:25:59.740 --> 00:26:07.030
the way to do that, I think, is to show
them that you're interested in learning.

00:26:07.030 --> 00:26:13.370
And it's sort of surprising to put it
that way, but if you don't seek them out

00:26:13.370 --> 00:26:19.400
and actually listen to what they're
saying and put it into some sort of

00:26:19.400 --> 00:26:24.500
practice, they're not going to think very
highly of you or really be very

00:26:24.500 --> 00:26:30.170
interested in working with you. So you
have to demonstrate your ambition

00:26:30.170 --> 00:26:37.160
basically. And the way that most people
do that is by working with them in a way

00:26:37.160 --> 00:26:42.920
where you're actually showing them that
you're taking their advice to heart and

00:26:42.920 --> 00:26:47.750
following through. That's actually the
most important thing. When a professor

00:26:47.750 --> 00:26:53.690
talks to you and makes suggestions it's not
enough to say those are nice. What counts

00:26:53.690 --> 00:26:59.410
is coming back and actually implementing
those suggestions in a positive way. So

00:26:59.410 --> 00:27:04.640
for me with Peter, and I'll say that the
first mentor I had

00:27:04.640 --> 00:27:13.460
was Nancy Weiss, later to become Nancy
Malkiel, and she was the first professor

00:27:13.460 --> 00:27:19.550
that I went to at office hours. And my
first question is why did you give me a

00:27:19.550 --> 00:27:28.700
C on my paper? And she didn't blow me off.
She actually explained why, and I took to

00:27:28.700 --> 00:27:37.250
heart her advice and got a B on my
final paper, but then went and found

00:27:37.250 --> 00:27:43.700
Peter, who because he taught Latin
American history understood some of my

00:27:43.700 --> 00:27:51.260
language difficulties in writing English
from a Spanish background. And so he was

00:27:51.260 --> 00:27:57.200
able to help me learn how to write
properly, but every time he gave me

00:27:57.200 --> 00:28:03.050
advice, the one thing I needed was my
next paper had to fix that problem. And I

00:28:03.050 --> 00:28:06.860
could, you know, you could make a mistake
once, but you shouldn't make it twice. And

00:28:06.860 --> 00:28:14.720
so by the time I finished with him four
years later, I began the process of

00:28:14.720 --> 00:28:22.220
writing in a way that led me to my law
degree and to being a judge. But when you

00:28:22.220 --> 00:28:29.030
go into the workplace, find people who
are doing things that you admire, that

00:28:29.030 --> 00:28:34.820
you don't think you can do, because
finding a mentor who is just going to

00:28:34.820 --> 00:28:40.760
show you what you know to me is not very
helpful to me. I always look for those

00:28:40.760 --> 00:28:48.410
mentors in my workplace that will help
me understand things and learn how to do

00:28:48.410 --> 00:28:57.110
things that I don't think I know how to
do. and so picking the two judges you did,

00:28:57.110 --> 00:29:01.280
and I know they had a lot to do in
picking you, obviously, but I'm sure you

00:29:01.280 --> 00:29:07.550
had alternatives. They both opened up
different worlds to you and that's what

00:29:07.550 --> 00:29:11.570
I've always tried to do with other
mentors throughout my life, to pick

00:29:11.570 --> 00:29:16.210
people who can teach me things I'm not
sure that I can do.

00:29:16.210 --> 00:29:25.160
KAGAN: Can I just say Professor Weiss did not
give me a very good grade either, so who

00:29:25.160 --> 00:29:29.090
knew that we had this in common.

00:29:29.090 --> 00:29:34.370
