00:30:17.630 --> 00:30:22.610
four hours, so worry about this later.
But but I think it, I imagine all of

00:30:22.610 --> 00:30:26.540
those students here are wondering
whether they really know what they want

00:30:26.540 --> 00:30:30.680
to do and whether they're gonna have the
courage to make that jump when they make

00:30:30.680 --> 00:30:32.429
it. So how did you know, Justice Kagan,

00:30:32.429 --> 00:30:33.460
when to make that jump?

00:30:33.460 --> 00:30:35.480
KAGAN: Yeah, so I mean, I did

00:30:35.480 --> 00:30:43.460
make a lot of jumps. Before I came to this job,
which has life tenure you know, so I'll

00:30:43.460 --> 00:30:48.160
be in this one awhile,
knock wood, but

00:30:53.480 --> 00:30:59.490
but basically I changed jobs every four
years or so. And then the in the deanship,

00:30:59.490 --> 00:31:05.159
I stayed six years. That was, there was a
lot, so you know, different strokes for

00:31:05.159 --> 00:31:08.279
different folks.
Some people they love just finding one

00:31:08.279 --> 00:31:11.429
thing, and they want to do it for the
rest of their lives and that's

00:31:11.429 --> 00:31:16.620
absolutely fantastic. But for me, the
variety of when you said law allows you

00:31:16.620 --> 00:31:21.179
to do that - the variety of things that I
was able to do was really part of the

00:31:21.179 --> 00:31:24.990
fun of putting together a legal career.
