people out there, and so it is I think
important for all of us for women to

00:42:30.550 --> 00:42:36.609
understand that no matter how hostile an
environment may seem, you have to look

00:42:36.609 --> 00:42:42.280
around for those people who will come
and stand with you and by you. Because

00:42:42.280 --> 00:42:51.490
they are there. And so I guess my point
remains we still have a long way to go,

00:42:51.490 --> 00:43:01.500
parroting an old cigarette ad, but it's
a lot shorter distance than when I started out.

00:43:01.500 --> 00:43:06.940
GERKEN: So I wonder if I might turn
a little bit to the court and in the

00:43:06.940 --> 00:43:11.590
moment in time in which we find
ourselves, so this is a really difficult

00:43:11.590 --> 00:43:15.490
moment in terms of politics with, and
there's an enormous amount of

00:43:15.490 --> 00:43:20.260
polarization and partisanship around. And
the court has always been understood

00:43:20.260 --> 00:43:25.540
as a neutral arbiter, and it's an
incredibly important thing but it's hard

00:43:25.540 --> 00:43:30.310
these days when when people have trouble
even talking to one another, let alone

00:43:30.310 --> 00:43:35.260
having a shared set of facts and
arguments. And I wonder how you think

00:43:35.260 --> 00:43:40.930
about your role on the court at this
moment and how you deal with the

00:43:40.930 --> 00:43:45.010
challenge that we all deal with, which is
making sure to be fair to the other side

00:43:45.010 --> 00:43:50.230
to see things as they really are, to
check your own views. And Justice Kagan I

00:43:50.230 --> 00:43:53.740
wonder if you might just start and talk
a little bit about that.

00:43:53.740 --> 00:43:55.720
KAGAN: You know, this is

00:43:55.720 --> 00:44:02.470
a really divided time, and part of the
court's strength and and part of the

00:44:02.470 --> 00:44:08.800
court's legitimacy depends on people not
seeing the court in the way that people

00:44:08.800 --> 00:44:15.130
see the rest of the governing structures
of this country now. In other words

00:44:15.130 --> 00:44:19.300
people thinking of the court as not
politically divided in the same way, as

00:44:19.300 --> 00:44:26.510
not an extension of politics, but instead
somehow above the fray, even

00:44:26.510 --> 00:44:32.300
if not always and in every case. And it's
an incredibly important thing for the

00:44:32.300 --> 00:44:39.260
court to guard, is is is this reputation
of of being fair, of being impartial, of

00:44:39.260 --> 00:44:46.550
being neutral, and of not being simply an
extension of the terribly polarized

00:44:46.550 --> 00:44:53.030
political process and environment that
we live in. And and you know that this is

00:44:53.030 --> 00:44:58.750
a challenge. There -
I think people too often don't realize

00:44:58.750 --> 00:45:05.150
that we agree on a lot. If you look at
the court's caseload as a whole, you'll

00:45:05.150 --> 00:45:10.340
find that about half the time we're
unanimous. On another big chunk of the

00:45:10.340 --> 00:45:16.310
time, we have very lopsided votes, but
there are some issues, some important

00:45:16.310 --> 00:45:21.850
issues that people care about, in which
the court is more closely divided and

00:45:21.850 --> 00:45:29.090
tends to be divided along lines that you
might predict if you looked at who

00:45:29.090 --> 00:45:34.250
nominated each of us. I think it's been
an extremely important thing for the

00:45:34.250 --> 00:45:40.970
court that, in the last really 30 years,
starting with Justice O'Connor and and

00:45:40.970 --> 00:45:47.120
continuing with Justice Kennedy, there
has been a person who people who found

00:45:47.120 --> 00:45:52.910
the center, or people couldn't predict in
that sort of way. And that's enabled the

00:45:52.910 --> 00:45:59.270
court to look as though it was not owned
by one side or another and and was

00:45:59.270 --> 00:46:08.300
indeed impartial and neutral and fair.
And it's not so clear that, you know, I

00:46:08.300 --> 00:46:17.180
think going forward that sort of middle
position, you know, it's not so clear

00:46:17.180 --> 00:46:25.280
whether we'll have it. And that puts, I
think all of us need to be aware of that,

00:46:25.280 --> 00:46:35.060
every single one of us, and to realize
how precious the court's legitimacy is.

00:46:35.060 --> 00:46:39.109
You know, we don't need, we don't have an
army and we don't have

00:46:39.109 --> 00:46:46.069
any money and the only way we get people
to do what we say that they should do is

00:46:46.069 --> 00:46:52.220
because people respect us and respect
our fairness. And I think especially in

00:46:52.220 --> 00:46:57.140
this time where the rest of the
political environment is so divided,

00:46:57.140 --> 00:47:03.920
every single one of us has an obligation
to think about what it is that provides

00:47:03.920 --> 00:47:09.890
the court with its legitimacy and has
you know to think about how we can be

00:47:09.890 --> 00:47:15.380
not so politically divided as some of
the other political institutions in the

00:47:15.380 --> 00:47:25.960
nation.
[APPLAUSE]

00:47:25.960 --> 00:47:36.589
SOTOMAYOR:I'd agree fully with everything 
Elena's saying. I think it's important to explain

00:47:36.589 --> 00:47:46.280
to people often that part of the
politicization of the court has come

00:47:46.280 --> 00:47:56.299
about because our political parties have
adopted the academic discussions that

00:47:56.299 --> 00:48:04.069
judges were having for the longest time
about how to interpret laws of the

00:48:04.069 --> 00:48:11.290
Constitution. And these were legal
discussions centered around originalism.

00:48:11.290 --> 00:48:16.640
Do you interpret the Constitution
according to what you discern the

00:48:16.640 --> 00:48:23.829
Founding Fathers would have done or
according to the plain meaning of words?

00:48:23.829 --> 00:48:32.599
Versus people who believed and still
believe that originalism has general

00:48:32.599 --> 00:48:38.510
principles but that, like our society
today, our Founding Fathers were never

00:48:38.510 --> 00:48:42.230
unanimous about what they thought the
answer should be.

00:48:42.230 --> 00:48:49.280
And they wrote very broad terms to let
generations that follow give those words

00:48:49.280 --> 00:48:56.809
meaning. And so you've got these two sets
of, between originalist and other people,

00:48:56.809 --> 00:49:04.040
and you've got plain meaning and people
who say no word is plain, because every

00:49:04.040 --> 00:49:09.140
word has to be read in context and
context shades the meaning of everything.

00:49:09.140 --> 00:49:20.240
And so those academic discussions have
often led to outcomes that some people

00:49:20.240 --> 00:49:28.430
can predic, not always but some. And when
the political parties adopted that

00:49:28.430 --> 00:49:35.480
language as their own, they've now
superimposed that on the court.

00:49:35.480 --> 00:49:42.050
So originalists get identified as the
choice of a certain group of politicians,

00:49:42.050 --> 00:49:46.160
not originalists, 
the choice of another group of a

00:49:46.160 --> 00:49:52.730
different party. And I think that that
institutionally has hurt the court a lot

00:49:52.730 --> 00:49:59.540
and may continue to do so. I do think
that there are structures within the

00:49:59.540 --> 00:50:06.890
court, not the least of which is our
modern understanding among, I believe now

00:50:06.890 --> 00:50:14.450
we're eight justices, eight justices that
we have to rise above partisanship in

00:50:14.450 --> 00:50:20.300
our personal relationships. That we have
to treat each other with respect and

00:50:20.300 --> 00:50:29.869
dignity and with a sense of amicability
that the rest of the world doesn't often

00:50:29.869 --> 00:50:35.340
share. Elena's relationship with Justice
Scalia is well-known.

00:50:35.340 --> 00:50:38.040
KAGAN: Even though he didn't 
invite me to his poker game.

00:50:38.040 --> 00:50:42.600
SOTOMAYOR: I know.
KAGAN: And apparently did you.

00:50:42.600 --> 00:50:49.940
SOTOMAYOR: But you went hunting with him, 
and I never would, but and and that same

00:50:49.940 --> 00:50:58.910
friendship, by the way with Ruth, and and
there Neil Gorsuch and I are doing a lot

00:50:58.910 --> 00:51:03.790
of work together in promoting civic
education in the United States and so

00:51:03.790 --> 00:51:07.620
[APPLAUSE]

00:51:07.620 --> 00:51:15.380
I think that our openness about
respecting one another is an example

00:51:15.380 --> 00:51:23.300
that's important for us to both maintain
and promote. Whether and how we can

00:51:23.300 --> 00:51:29.810
accommodate the differences in our
judicial approaches is a much more

00:51:29.810 --> 00:51:37.760
difficult question. As on some things as
Justice Ginsberg once said, It's hard.

00:51:37.760 --> 00:51:44.600
It's a compromise on fundamental
Constitutional principles and a lot of

00:51:44.600 --> 00:51:51.620
those things are what lead to the 5-4
decisions that the public seems to think

00:51:51.620 --> 00:51:59.090
are divisive, but we do manage to agree
on lots of things. And to the extent we

00:51:59.090 --> 00:52:07.700
can avoid ruling in such expansive ways
as to foreclose continued conversation, I

00:52:07.700 --> 00:52:13.550
think we have a chance of holding on to
our legitimacy. As Elena says, though,

00:52:13.550 --> 00:52:20.080
we're each going to have to think about
how to do that and how to implement and

00:52:20.080 --> 00:52:28.380
support our institutional reputation.
GERKEN: So this follows nicely on one of the

00:52:28.380 --> 00:52:30.700
questions from the audience, because I

00:52:30.700 --> 00:52:33.140
am struck, you know. I read your 5-4

00:52:33.140 --> 00:52:37.880
opinions. You are fierce lawyers. You know
sometimes when you're reading the, hit her

00:52:37.880 --> 00:52:42.440
again hit it again. You know it's really,
the lawyer in me is so impressed with

00:52:42.440 --> 00:52:49.040
it's hard-hitting, it's frank. You know when
you disagree, you you disagree in a in a

00:52:49.040 --> 00:52:54.650
respectful but powerful way. And then I
know how collegial you all are with one

00:52:54.650 --> 00:52:57.350
another when you walk off that bench. 
I think that's something that most people

00:52:57.350 --> 00:53:01.610
don't see and don't know. And and Justice Kagan I wonder if you might talk a little

00:53:01.610 --> 00:53:07.010
bit about what are the rituals of
respect that exist inside the court. Is

00:53:07.010 --> 00:53:11.060
it the deliberative process? What is it
that you do that enables you to do

00:53:11.060 --> 00:53:14.270
something that almost no one else is
able to do at this moment in time, which

00:53:14.270 --> 00:53:18.590
is to be friends with the people with
whom you disagree fiercely?

00:53:18.590 --> 00:53:21.200
KAGAN: Well I'll say first of all 
that I think that there is a little

00:53:21.280 --> 00:53:26.020
bit of self-interest going on here,
because we live in this this this this

00:53:26.030 --> 00:53:31.520
world where it's just a nine of us. We
are the consummate repeat players. Every

00:53:31.520 --> 00:53:38.330
case, it's going to be the same nine of
us. And if you hold grudges, or if you you

00:53:38.330 --> 00:53:42.320
know have a bad relationship with one of
your colleagues, then in the next case

00:53:42.320 --> 00:53:47.650
and in the next case and in the next
case, you have a not much of a chance of

00:53:47.650 --> 00:53:51.440
persuading that colleague to come along
with what you think is the right thing

00:53:51.440 --> 00:53:56.750
to do. So so we all have a kind of vested
interest in having good relations with

00:53:56.750 --> 00:54:01.490
each other, and I think that that's part
of what maintains our good behavior. But

00:54:01.490 --> 00:54:04.580
I will say that I think that it's it's
it's something more than that. And I

00:54:04.580 --> 00:54:07.730
don't think it's necessary - if you look
at the history of the Supreme Court,

00:54:07.730 --> 00:54:11.890
there are some parts of the court's
history where people had completely

00:54:11.890 --> 00:54:18.770
pathological relationships, where they
wouldn't talk with each other, where one

00:54:18.770 --> 00:54:23.180
person walked into a room and another
person would walk out. And we don't have

00:54:23.180 --> 00:54:25.267
any of that. We actually -

00:54:25.267 --> 00:54:30.050
SOTOMAYOR: Read "Scorpions"
by Noah Feldman. It's a wonderful read

00:54:30.050 --> 00:54:35.800
even for non-lawyers, and it we'll talk
about that, one of those periods in our history.

00:54:35.800 --> 00:54:39.920
KAGAN: Absolutely. And we are very much
not like that. I think we all get along

00:54:39.920 --> 00:54:46.400
genuinely very well. I think we we we all
believe that everybody is operating in

00:54:46.400 --> 00:54:52.670
good faith around the table, even if we
disagree strongly with them. You know so

00:54:52.670 --> 00:54:56.570
what what what what accounts for that
I'm not sure. I think partly it's

00:54:56.570 --> 00:55:01.790
personalities. I think that the the chief
justice is very good about setting the

00:55:01.790 --> 00:55:10.160
tone that for the entire institution. We
have lunch all the time. Now this might

00:55:10.160 --> 00:55:15.050
seem it's a little thing, but every time
we have arguments, and every time we meet

00:55:15.050 --> 00:55:20.870
in conference to talk about cases, we
always follow that by with a lunch

00:55:20.870 --> 00:55:25.370
together in the justices dining room.
And there are rules about, you can't talk

00:55:25.370 --> 00:55:30.410
about work, you can't talk about cases,
you can so we got to know a lot about

00:55:30.410 --> 00:55:34.400
you know each other's families.
Or we talk about books or movies or

00:55:34.400 --> 00:55:39.440
sports, or you know various things, and
you know it just 
SOTOMAYOR: We tell bad jokes

00:55:39.440 --> 00:55:45.800
KAGAN: We tell bad jokes. I won't say 
which of our colleagues are sort of the

00:55:45.800 --> 00:55:54.620
Masters of the bad jokes okay. It's
neither of the two of us, but you know we

00:55:54.620 --> 00:56:02.000
laugh, we groan, and I think that those
kinds of I don't know whether to

00:56:02.000 --> 00:56:08.210
call lunch an institutional
arrangement, but sort of do help to keep

00:56:08.210 --> 00:56:12.020
things a little bit lighter than they
might otherwise be. So you know we do get

00:56:12.020 --> 00:56:17.930
annoyed with each other sometimes, and as
the year goes by the annoyances tend to

00:56:17.930 --> 00:56:21.530
add up a little bit. So I've always
thought that, much as in the academic

00:56:21.530 --> 00:56:25.130
environment, one of the great things
about really getting along with each

00:56:25.130 --> 00:56:30.800
other is that we get to escape each
other in the summers. And you you know,

00:56:30.800 --> 00:56:35.480
you you escape each other. You you're
away from people and you actually, when

00:56:35.480 --> 00:56:39.410
you when you come back, you realize how
much you miss them and how much you like

00:56:39.410 --> 00:56:48.020
them and how much you appreciate them.
SOTOMAYOR: How I do it in life generally is I try

00:56:48.020 --> 00:56:54.920
to find the good in every person. If you
start from the proposition that there is

00:56:54.920 --> 00:57:04.040
something good in everybody, it's a lot
easier to get along with them,

00:57:04.040 --> 00:57:15.800
even when you disagree vehemently.
And so for me, I tell people often who don't

00:57:15.800 --> 00:57:23.000
know, Justice Clarence Thomas knows every
employee in our building, and not only

00:57:23.000 --> 00:57:29.120
knows their names, but he knows all their
family members. If someone gets ill, he's

00:57:29.120 --> 00:57:34.580
the first one to reach out and offer help.

00:57:34.580 --> 00:57:41.339
He is exceedingly caring 
whenever anyone, myself I can

00:57:41.339 --> 00:57:45.539
speak for myself, but I know he does it
with everybody. If you're ill, if you've

00:57:45.539 --> 00:57:51.989
had someone die in your family, his are
the first flowers that arrive. It's the

00:57:51.989 --> 00:57:56.009
first call that's made 
to see if you're okay.

00:57:56.009 --> 00:58:05.009
He and I I don't think voted together on
hardly anything, but I know that inside

00:58:05.009 --> 00:58:08.869
of him there is a goodness 
that I can admire.

00:58:08.869 --> 00:58:18.599
Might disagree with him on everything
else, but I think if you can approach

00:58:18.599 --> 00:58:23.549
people in that way and understand that a
difference of opinion doesn't

00:58:23.549 --> 00:58:31.589
necessarily brand you an evil person,
there's more space to talk, there's more

00:58:31.589 --> 00:58:42.989
space to engage, and certainly more space
for willingness to compromise. And you

00:58:42.989 --> 00:58:50.759
know the master of that was probably
Tony Kennedy. Tony Kennedy I think spent

00:58:50.759 --> 00:58:56.669
all of his time trying to find the best
in his colleagues and I think that's why

00:58:56.669 --> 00:59:00.680
he could find middle ground so often.

00:59:00.680 --> 00:59:04.799
GERKEN: One of the things that is
so striking about your opinions and

00:59:04.799 --> 00:59:09.809
particularly your dissents is that they
speak to people who don't have law

00:59:09.809 --> 00:59:14.069
degrees. So law can be very technical.
When judges write, they often write quite

00:59:14.069 --> 00:59:21.299
abstractly, but you two are both able to
crystallize issues in a way that's

00:59:21.299 --> 00:59:24.659
accessible to people who are reading the
newspaper. I actually think in some ways

00:59:24.659 --> 00:59:28.709
you share that with Justice Scalia, that
you're able to read it and understand

00:59:28.709 --> 00:59:33.779
the stakes and it's very powerful.
I wonder, especially when you're writing

00:59:33.779 --> 00:59:39.269
dissents, how do you think about uses of
emotion, how do you think

00:59:39.269 --> 00:59:43.829
about that crisp phrase that's you know
is gonna be in the front page of the New

00:59:43.829 --> 00:59:46.160
York Times?
How do you think about when to do it,

00:59:46.160 --> 00:59:49.999
when to play that card and when not to
play that card? And I ask you in

00:59:49.999 --> 00:59:52.460
particular because there is some
possibility that you may be dissenting

00:59:52.460 --> 00:59:57.980
more often in the future, and so I wonder
you know if you imagine yourselves as

00:59:57.980 --> 01:00:03.200
lawyers, as justices, but also as
dissenters, how do you how do you think

01:00:03.200 --> 01:00:08.119
about how you write the opinion and and
when to play this sort of one of those

01:00:08.119 --> 01:00:11.450
cards? And Justice Sotomayor, I wonder if
I might talk to you because I know you

01:00:11.450 --> 01:00:15.619
know sometimes you speak quite
personally, even emotionally, in some of

01:00:15.619 --> 01:00:18.859
your dissents. And I wonder if you might
talk about when you think about doing

01:00:18.860 --> 01:00:28.400
that and why. 
SOTOMAYOR: I lost two cases in a row

01:00:28.400 --> 01:00:32.660
early in my career as a prosecutor and I

01:00:32.660 --> 01:00:37.700
went to my supervisor, and he sat down
and he said how did you present your

01:00:37.700 --> 01:00:42.619
case, cases? And I went through it and he
said, My

01:00:42.619 --> 01:00:54.410
that's so logical. That's why you lost.
You didn't convince the jury that it was

01:00:54.410 --> 01:01:03.259
their obligation to convict. And I looked
at him and I said what? And he said, you

01:01:03.259 --> 01:01:11.509
know jurors are human beings who don't
want to pass judgment on another person,

01:01:11.509 --> 01:01:19.579
and it's very hard for them to say that
person is guilty or to imagine that

01:01:19.579 --> 01:01:26.210
maybe that person is going to go to jail.
And when you're presenting your case, you

01:01:26.210 --> 01:01:33.109
have to not only convince them that this
is what the evidence proves, but that

01:01:33.109 --> 01:01:40.819
it's also their obligation to convict. He
said that to me and I did not lose

01:01:40.819 --> 01:01:46.819
another case and I think I tried 30
cases after that. I had a couple of hung

01:01:46.819 --> 01:01:55.930
juries and I'd had a couple of less than
the top charges, but I never lost another.

01:01:55.930 --> 01:02:06.020
Now it doesn't mean I when I write that
way you have to marshal the evidence. You

01:02:06.020 --> 01:02:16.760
have to prove the case. But you have to
convince a reader of the moral justice

01:02:16.760 --> 01:02:24.620
in your position. And I think that it's
not every case requires that. You know

01:02:24.620 --> 01:02:32.360
we've got more than 50% of cases that
that we agree upon, and I if I wrote that

01:02:32.360 --> 01:02:38.990
way for all 50 of those, I'd never get a
unanimous court again. But we do because

01:02:38.990 --> 01:02:45.080
we write in certain ways when you have,
you're trying to draw more votes. But

01:02:45.080 --> 01:02:51.950
when there is something that you
understand to be fundamental and if you

01:02:51.950 --> 01:02:58.400
want to have people understand your
position and what you're arguing, then I

01:02:58.400 --> 01:03:06.760
do think that explaining it in a way
that people can feel is critical. I

01:03:06.760 --> 01:03:12.020
probably don't do it more than once or
twice a year, because it has to be that

01:03:12.020 --> 01:03:20.150
fundamental case that people need to
understand and need to understand that

01:03:20.150 --> 01:03:33.230
the choice is right under the law. And so
for me it's not hard to come to those

01:03:33.230 --> 01:03:39.560
moments. I do think that writing so
people understand your cases or your

01:03:39.560 --> 01:03:44.690
position is always important. Writing the
most complex case in simple ways is

01:03:44.690 --> 01:03:50.000
terribly important but I will tell you
even though we work hard at that, I bet

01:03:50.000 --> 01:03:53.960
the majority of people never read a
Supreme Court case.

01:03:53.960 --> 01:03:59.610
They read the the quips in the New York
Times. They read summaries in some other

01:03:59.610 --> 01:04:06.210
form. If I were to ask this room how
many of you have read a Supreme Court

01:04:06.210 --> 01:04:14.250
case cover to cover, I bet that
two-thirds of you never have. And so you

01:04:14.250 --> 01:04:19.770
do it in the hopes that the person who
does pick it up will understand and in

01:04:19.770 --> 01:04:24.990
the hope that if what you're explaining
can touch people, that they will read more

01:04:24.990 --> 01:04:28.200
than they normally do.
GERKEN: Justice Kagan, I wonder if I

01:04:28.200 --> 01:04:31.920
might ask you the same question. There was
a First Amendment case this year where

01:04:31.920 --> 01:04:39.360
you wrote extremely powerful dissent and
crystallized a set of cases and as they

01:04:39.360 --> 01:04:43.380
were moving through, and when when we all
read that phrase "the weaponization of

01:04:43.380 --> 01:04:47.910
the First Amendment" it was it was
something that everyone in the academy

01:04:47.910 --> 01:04:51.420
stood up and listened, and all the lawyers
stood up and listened. It was really

01:04:51.420 --> 01:04:55.530
powerful, because we knew you don't do
that often. And I just wonder, how did you

01:04:55.530 --> 01:04:59.900
think about, without being too specific
about any case, how do you think about this?

01:04:59.900 --> 01:05:02.640
KAGAN: Right, you don't do it often and you
can't do it often for just the reasons

01:05:02.640 --> 01:05:06.840
that Justice Sotomayor said, is you know,
there are different kinds of dissents.

01:05:06.840 --> 01:05:10.050
There are dissents where you think
that the majority has gotten it wrong,

01:05:10.050 --> 01:05:14.850
and you think, you know, I should say that
there's another way to understand this

01:05:14.850 --> 01:05:18.180
question, but in the next case, in the
next case, in the next case, you're going

01:05:18.180 --> 01:05:22.620
going to go along with the majority's
position. You've had your say, now it's

01:05:22.620 --> 01:05:28.230
time to to join the precedent that's
been created and nothing about your

01:05:28.230 --> 01:05:34.740
dissent in a case like that ought to be
you know, so so powerful. Right? You

01:05:34.740 --> 01:05:39.630
should try to tell people why you're
right, but it's not, the

01:05:39.630 --> 01:05:43.620
world doesn't depend on it. But every
once in a while, you you see a case which

01:05:43.620 --> 01:05:47.850
seems - sometimes these cases they stand
in for bigger issues. It's not just the

01:05:47.850 --> 01:05:52.950
case itself. It's what you fear the case
signifies for the future. It's what, it's

01:05:52.950 --> 01:05:57.300
it's the case, and the next case, and the
next case, and you can see how the court

01:05:57.300 --> 01:06:02.280
is going down a road that you think is
profoundly dangerous, and and then you

01:06:02.280 --> 01:06:06.030
have to say so, and you have to say what
you find dangerous about it and why you

01:06:06.030 --> 01:06:09.390
think that there that there is this danger.

01:06:09.390 --> 01:06:16.440
And and you know, in an attempt, if not
now, then next year or next year, or the

01:06:16.440 --> 01:06:22.130
year after that, or 10 years or 20 years,
you know to get people to reevaluate

01:06:22.130 --> 01:06:26.610
where that, what the court has done and
where the court is going. And those

01:06:26.610 --> 01:06:29.580
dissents have to be written in a
different way if you're really speaking

01:06:29.580 --> 01:06:33.930
to the next generation and if you're
saying here's what the court has done

01:06:33.930 --> 01:06:41.790
wrong and here's how we you know need
to reverse this, I mean you got up your

01:06:41.790 --> 01:06:48.330
rhetoric a little bit. Now I tend not to,
I think like some of the opinions that

01:06:48.330 --> 01:06:57.060
Sonia has written that are emotional are
really powerful, but I tend not to try to

01:06:57.060 --> 01:07:03.870
get people to feel things, but I it's
just sort of not the way I write, but but

01:07:03.870 --> 01:07:10.680
but I want them to think they have
gotten it so wrong.

01:07:10.680 --> 01:07:18.270
And so I guess I guess maybe to feel
that, to feel to feel that their logic,

01:07:18.270 --> 01:07:26.640
that their legal analysis, their use of
precedent, that and their, you know, that

01:07:26.640 --> 01:07:38.940
their selection of fundamental legal
principles is is just really wrong.

01:07:38.940 --> 01:07:40.680
SOTOMAYOR: We are very different.

01:07:40.680 --> 01:07:43.300
KAGAN: So that's what you
try to do, what I try to do.

01:07:43.380 --> 01:07:44.760
GERKEN: I wonder if I might ask you a little bit about

01:07:44.760 --> 01:07:47.660
being a first. There was only four women who have

01:07:47.670 --> 01:07:53.640
worn this robe. I remember when Justice
Ginsburg joined the court, and she was up

01:07:53.640 --> 01:07:58.680
there with Justice O'Connor, and one of
the advocates mixed them up, even though

01:07:58.680 --> 01:08:03.630
I'll just say, they really don't look
anything alike, different politics

01:08:03.630 --> 01:08:07.620
different different accents, everything
you could ask for. And so yeah there's a

01:08:07.620 --> 01:08:11.340
lot of studies about what happens with
women on the bench, do they get

01:08:11.340 --> 01:08:16.050
interrupted more, how do counsel treat
them, do they mix them up for one another,

01:08:16.050 --> 01:08:21.870
and I wonder when you have, when you
put that robe on, do you feel it? Do you

01:08:21.870 --> 01:08:26.400
feel that gap or are you un-self-conscious about your gender?

01:08:26.420 --> 01:08:30.080
I'm just curious about how you how you inhabit
that role, maybe Justice Kagan?

01:08:30.090 --> 01:08:33.900
KAGAN: I really don't feel it on the bench.
There have actually been these these these

01:08:33.900 --> 01:08:38.400
studies recently that have surprised me,
because they're so not in keeping with

01:08:38.400 --> 01:08:44.850
my experience of it there. And the
studies they insist that the women on

01:08:44.850 --> 01:08:49.290
the bench, and particularly the two of us,
get interrupted more than our male

01:08:49.290 --> 01:08:56.190
colleagues still, in a way that you know
in lots of other parts of my life, that

01:08:56.190 --> 01:09:01.440
has struck me as a common experience,
that women get interrupted more than men

01:09:01.440 --> 01:09:05.870
do, that women have an idea and nobody
really responds to it and then a man

01:09:05.870 --> 01:09:12.740
repeats the idea and everybody says, Wow,
that is amazing.

01:09:16.350 --> 01:09:20.070
But I have to say that on the bench I
think that those statistics about

01:09:20.070 --> 01:09:24.600
interruption have much more to do with
the fact that there's, that Sonia and I

01:09:24.600 --> 01:09:28.950
are relatively junior justices and that
there is a practice of, if two people

01:09:28.950 --> 01:09:32.490
start talking at the same time, which is
often the case at the court because

01:09:32.490 --> 01:09:37.020
there are a lot of talkers on the court,
and and and so the moment you see a

01:09:37.020 --> 01:09:41.520
sort of pause, you jump, two people jump
in, and one of them has to step back. And

01:09:41.520 --> 01:09:46.350
I think we tend to step back a little
bit because we're junior justices, but my

01:09:46.350 --> 01:09:52.770
sense of the bench now is, you know, there
are three women on the bench and Justice

01:09:52.770 --> 01:09:56.640
Sotomayor and I sit on opposite sides of
the bench, and Justice Ginsburg sits in

01:09:56.640 --> 01:10:02.610
the middle. None of us are shrinking
violets. We all, you know, ask lots of

01:10:02.610 --> 01:10:09.840
questions. We all can give lawyers a good
run for their money, and I think if you

01:10:09.840 --> 01:10:14.250
come to the Supreme Court, it's like wow
there are these women's voices from all

01:10:14.250 --> 01:10:18.510
over the place, from this side and that
side, in the center, and and they're just

01:10:18.510 --> 01:10:26.700
kind of coming at you. And it seems to me
we don't take a backseat role.

01:10:26.700 --> 01:10:30.040
SOTOMAYOR: I was just gonna say that I don't disbelieve

01:10:30.040 --> 01:10:34.980
the statistics. 
I accept them as true. I

01:10:34.980 --> 01:10:41.640
think the difference is that not one of
us three are shrinking violets, and we

01:10:41.640 --> 01:10:44.540
just don't care.
[APPLAUSE]

01:10:50.820 --> 01:10:57.040
Because of it and because I think we
just accept it and just move on from

01:10:57.040 --> 01:11:02.110
there, and it doesn't stop us from doing
whatever we think we need to do, or

01:11:02.110 --> 01:11:06.430
getting a clarification to a question we
think is important, that it really

01:11:06.430 --> 01:11:15.060
doesn't affect us. You know it was Ruth
who at a public event not so long ago

01:11:15.060 --> 01:11:20.830
said and this may be true for her for a
slightly different reason, Justice

01:11:20.830 --> 01:11:27.760
Ginsberg speaks very softly and it's
sometimes very hard to hear her, but she

01:11:27.760 --> 01:11:33.700
said that there were moments where she
would say something and go around the

01:11:33.700 --> 01:11:38.530
table and some male in our group would
say something and it was a great idea

01:11:38.530 --> 01:11:43.330
coming from him and not her. Whether
that's because of the softness of her

01:11:43.330 --> 01:11:50.140
tone or gender dynamics in place it's
hard to tell, but I do think it does

01:11:50.140 --> 01:12:00.190
happen, and but I do think that given the
nature of the court and the fact that we

01:12:00.190 --> 01:12:06.310
all understand that we're one among nine
and that our votes are equal in that

01:12:06.310 --> 01:12:11.160
respect, that it doesn't affect us as
much.

01:12:11.160 --> 01:12:13.380
GERKEN: So it's a great job you have so I

01:12:13.390 --> 01:12:18.340
know you won't be complaining, but but it
does require you to give things up. You

01:12:18.340 --> 01:12:21.340
know the different roles require
different things of you. I mean Justice

01:12:21.340 --> 01:12:24.340
Kagan, I remember speaking to you just
after you become Solicitor General and

01:12:24.340 --> 01:12:29.170
you'd left running this giant law school.
You have this extraordinary law school,

01:12:29.170 --> 01:12:33.490
this massive operation, and students,
faculty, alumni, all these things and and

01:12:33.490 --> 01:12:38.800
I remember you said the phone doesn't
ring that much when you were SG, and I

01:12:38.800 --> 01:12:42.580
imagine you both now are in a completely
different role than you've been before.

01:12:42.580 --> 01:12:46.450
So I wonder as you think what is it that
you'd given up, what is it what are the

01:12:46.450 --> 01:12:49.930
things you can't do, the things that you
can't say, that you would have done in an

01:12:49.930 --> 01:12:56.500
instant at some other point because
you're both reasonably blunt. So I'm curious.

01:12:56.660 --> 01:12:58.800
KAGAN: The phone doesn't ring. I track my jobs

01:12:58.800 --> 01:13:03.360
in terms of emails received. I used to,
when I was dean, used to get 400

01:13:03.360 --> 01:13:07.170
500 emails a day, and then when
I was Solicitor General, I got about 40.

01:13:07.170 --> 01:13:17.100
And now, when I get an email, it is such
an exciting moment in my life. I don't know.

01:13:17.100 --> 01:13:20.910
You know you know different different
different jobs have different

01:13:20.910 --> 01:13:26.040
constraints that go along with them. And
and I've been in other jobs too where I

01:13:26.040 --> 01:13:31.230
haven't been able to to do whatever I
wanted to do or to say whatever I

01:13:31.230 --> 01:13:36.920
wanted to say. You're a dean. I mean my
view of the deanship was that as to

01:13:36.920 --> 01:13:41.460
various issues that my students and my
faculty and my alumni were very divided

01:13:41.460 --> 01:13:45.900
on that my job was to trying to be
neutral and and to play it straight. And

01:13:45.900 --> 01:13:55.260
and so I think I'm I'm used to feeling
that there are some, every job has, what

01:13:55.260 --> 01:13:59.520
goes along with the job is some set of
constraints. This is what you can't do

01:13:59.520 --> 01:14:03.960
and still be able to do your job
effectively and well and according to

01:14:03.960 --> 01:14:11.730
the ethical rules of the job or or that
will allow you to serve the goals of the

01:14:11.730 --> 01:14:17.910
job. And so this job doesn't feel all
that different to me from others in that

01:14:17.910 --> 01:14:24.570
respect. That sure there's a lot of stuff that I can't 
talk in public about. There's some stuff that I feel

01:14:24.570 --> 01:14:31.860
as though I shouldn't even really think
about, but I think that's that's true

01:14:31.860 --> 01:14:34.448
most things in the world.

01:14:34.448 --> 01:14:39.210
SOTOMAYOR: I don't disagree with 
the basic point but I do

01:14:39.210 --> 01:14:47.550
think that, more than the other jobs I
had, and I was a judge for 17 years

01:14:47.550 --> 01:14:56.420
before this, first of all I won't wear
shorts anymore.

01:14:56.800 --> 01:15:02.360
You do have to be careful about what you
wear, which when I was a judge before it

01:15:02.360 --> 01:15:06.320
people would never think of taking a
picture of me when I walked around my

01:15:06.320 --> 01:15:13.360
neighborhood. Now that I'm a justice they
would and they do. I'm careful at beaches.

01:15:13.360 --> 01:15:21.800
You know, I, but that also goes to my
conversation in public. When I was a

01:15:21.800 --> 01:15:25.969
regular judge, whatever that means but
when I was a judge on the court of

01:15:25.969 --> 01:15:31.849
appeals and on the district court, I
could go and express an opinion to a

01:15:31.849 --> 01:15:43.219
friend privately and never had to fear
that it would go public. That's not quite

01:15:43.219 --> 01:15:50.260
the same today and not because I don't
think my friends intend to spread

01:15:50.260 --> 01:15:57.920
private comments, but they inadvertently
might say something to a friend who then

01:15:57.920 --> 01:16:04.190
will report it publicly. And that sort
of thing makes you much more guarded

01:16:04.190 --> 01:16:11.210
than I ever thought I had to be before.
And even when you tell jokes, people take

01:16:11.210 --> 01:16:17.719
them seriously. You you get stuff back
and calls from the press, did you say

01:16:17.719 --> 01:16:27.770
this and you go what? There
is, you give up quite a bit of public

01:16:27.770 --> 01:16:35.030
life and being open and blunt but it
also I think to some degree makes you

01:16:35.030 --> 01:16:39.780
more guarded even in your private life.

01:16:39.780 --> 01:16:44.140
GERKEN: So now I'm goint to ask about your private life, since a lot of the questions wanted to just know

01:16:44.150 --> 01:16:50.389
just this one simple question, what on
earth do you do for fun and and if I

01:16:50.389 --> 01:16:54.690
just may ask my own version of it, which
of you is a better poker player?

01:16:54.690 --> 01:17:00.180
KAGAN: She is! 
SOTOMAYOR: That's really,

01:17:00.280 --> 01:17:06.719
we both like poker. We
have fun with that. I love food and I

01:17:06.719 --> 01:17:12.870
love going to great restaurants. I have
champagne and beer tastes, so I can go

01:17:12.870 --> 01:17:17.520
very high-end and I can go to dives, and
I love both of them.

01:17:17.520 --> 01:17:22.230
I do bicycle ride when I'm not injured.
This year you know has been a bad year

01:17:22.230 --> 01:17:28.890
for me, and I like spending time with my
friends. I like cooking. I like you know

01:17:28.890 --> 01:17:35.820
just laughing about things that's not my
work. So I do have fun. Actually this is

01:17:35.820 --> 01:17:40.739
fun. I don't I don't -
Elena and I work together, we're in

01:17:40.739 --> 01:17:44.460
conference together, we're in the court
together, but it's rare that we have a

01:17:44.460 --> 01:17:49.960
plane ride here together or just a few
hours just to pass the time.

01:17:50.060 --> 01:17:53.240
KAGAN: Sometimes we go out for a meal. 
The two of us definitely know more restaurants in

01:17:53.340 --> 01:17:56.620
Washington D.C. than any of our colleagues -

01:17:56.620 --> 01:17:59.090
SOTOMAYOR: Put together, yeah, we
do, we do.

01:17:59.090 --> 01:18:03.100
So I know you read a lot.

01:18:03.100 --> 01:18:06.040
KAGAN: I read a lot. I
go to movies.

01:18:06.040 --> 01:18:09.620
SOTOMAYOR: That I don't do as much.

01:18:09.620 --> 01:18:17.240
KAGAN: Try to do some exercise every once in
a while, see friends, normal things. And

01:18:17.240 --> 01:18:20.870
actually you know what, it affects your
life a lot less than you might think, at

01:18:20.870 --> 01:18:26.810
least for me. I think Sonia's a little
bit more recognized than I am, or maybe a

01:18:26.810 --> 01:18:33.890
lot more recognized, because her face is
on the cover of all of these books, but I

01:18:33.890 --> 01:18:39.350
find for me that as long as I put on a
hat and sunglasses, so so in the winter

01:18:39.350 --> 01:18:44.780
it's a little bit weird, you know, to put
on the sunglasses, but I could do most

01:18:44.780 --> 01:18:51.110
things without without making a scene.
You know, sometimes I'll be aware, I'll be

01:18:51.110 --> 01:18:55.250
in a restaurant and I'll be, you know,
people will be like over there, you know,

01:18:55.250 --> 01:18:59.900
but Washington D.C. has its share of
public officials. and I think people

01:18:59.900 --> 01:19:05.380
don't get all that terribly excited
about seeing another one. And,

01:19:05.380 --> 01:19:10.060
you know, for the most part, we live very
normal lives.

01:19:10.060 --> 01:19:12.320
GERKEN: Alright, this is just a quick one.

01:19:12.320 --> 01:19:15.280
If this we're not your, the job of your
destiny, what would be the job of your

01:19:15.280 --> 01:19:18.460
destiny, if you could just pick any job
other than this one that you have, what

01:19:18.469 --> 01:19:20.620
would you do? 
KAGAN: That you really want to do?

01:19:20.620 --> 01:19:21.860
GERKEN: That you really want to do.
KAGAN: Even if you have none

01:19:21.860 --> 01:19:24.240
of the talents? 
GERKEN: None of the talents. You can

01:19:24.240 --> 01:19:28.680
trapeze artist if you want to pick it. What would you do?

01:19:28.680 --> 01:19:32.860
SOTOMAYOR: Oh you're gonna have to answer that. No I'll tell you why I'm in my

01:19:32.870 --> 01:19:39.050
perfect position, but I don't mean as a
Supreme Court justice. I loved being a

01:19:39.050 --> 01:19:43.130
lawyer, I loved being a district court
judge, circuit court judge. I love being a

01:19:43.130 --> 01:19:51.739
Supreme Court justice. The law was my
dream and I have always been happy in my

01:19:51.739 --> 01:19:57.909
life in my life. There really wasn't
anything that I could aspire to be like

01:19:57.909 --> 01:20:07.719
that except maybe a salsa dancer.
You know, because I couldn't do it and

01:20:07.719 --> 01:20:13.190
because even now I do it, but I don't do
it with the natural grace that I would

01:20:13.190 --> 01:20:21.260
love if I could have found that talent. I
would have been Rita Moreno on stage, you

01:20:21.260 --> 01:20:23.863
know, something like that, yeah.

01:20:23.863 --> 01:20:32.200
KAGAN: I think I'd be Serena Williams or something.
[LAUGHTER]

01:20:32.200 --> 01:20:36.440
but but then I doubt that she'd still be
doing it at my age, so I'm glad I have

01:20:36.440 --> 01:20:39.300
this job instead.
[LAUGHTER]

01:20:39.300 --> 01:20:44.900
SOTOMAYOR: Think of Billie Jean King. How old was she when she played Bobby Riggs?

01:20:44.900 --> 01:20:50.360
KAGAN: Definitely younger than I am now.
[LAUGHTER]

01:20:50.420 --> 01:20:53.480
GERKEN: I'm going to say the one thing that's gonna 
displease everyone in this room, which is this is

01:20:53.480 --> 01:21:00.180
our last question, and so I wonder if I
just might ask you a question about the

01:21:00.180 --> 01:21:04.020
effect that Princeton had on you. I mean
this is a place where we all came to

01:21:04.020 --> 01:21:08.520
grow up. We all began our professional
lives. We have a set of memories. I'm

01:21:08.520 --> 01:21:12.810
struck Justice Sotomayor, when I came
back as trustees, how embedded it was

01:21:12.810 --> 01:21:17.240
even just in the physical layout of the
place, that memories just flooded back to

01:21:17.240 --> 01:21:24.560
me, and so I wonder as you look back, what
has stuck with you from Princeton.

01:21:24.560 --> 01:21:32.840
SOTOMAYOR: It easier for me to answer this, because 
it was so transformational for me, and it

01:21:32.850 --> 01:21:40.050
affected my entire existing life then
and everything that has come since.

01:21:40.050 --> 01:21:46.640
It opened the door to opportunity for me in
a way that I never imagined, even when I

01:21:46.640 --> 01:21:54.590
accepted attending Princeton. I tell a
story in my book of my mother and I

01:21:54.590 --> 01:21:59.940
shopping for a raincoat that I could
bring with me to Princeton. And we were

01:21:59.940 --> 01:22:08.940
shopping in the South Bronx's most famous
shopping area, at Alexander's for those

01:22:08.940 --> 01:22:18.750
of those - it was a little less than
Macy's, lot less, but we were treated with

01:22:18.750 --> 01:22:22.489
such awe by the salespeople
when I told them I was attending

01:22:22.489 --> 01:22:28.980
Princeton. And as we walked out my mother
looked at me and said, what have you

01:22:28.980 --> 01:22:32.349
gotten us into now?

01:22:32.349 --> 01:22:40.599
And I didn't know. I didn't really
understand what it meant to come to a

01:22:40.599 --> 01:22:46.599
place like Princeton and all of the
changes that it would create in me. How

01:22:46.599 --> 01:22:51.639
much I would grow up, not just in my
writing skills and my thinking skills,

01:22:51.639 --> 01:22:56.440
but in my life skills, getting along with
people who were so vastly different from

01:22:56.440 --> 01:23:04.119
me. And so that gift is one I treasure. It is

01:23:04.119 --> 01:23:19.780
my enduring, my enduring gift from
Princeton. And so it took lots of years

01:23:19.780 --> 01:23:25.000
to be convinced to become a trustee,
because I was so busy in my life, and

01:23:25.000 --> 01:23:31.810
when I finally did I was so glad I had.
And it's my hope that more women in this

01:23:31.810 --> 01:23:37.690
room will aspire to that, because it's
still important to have women trustees

01:23:37.690 --> 01:23:47.619
